    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Broken link building</strong> is an off-page SEO tactic where you find dead links on relevant third-party websites, create or identify replacement content on your own site, and email the site owner asking them to update the broken link to yours. It works because webmasters actively want to fix broken links — outreach that helps them do it converts at 5-15%, well above cold link-building averages.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Response rate</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Avg broken outbound</div>
            <div class="tms-value">5-15% per site</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Cold outreach is the hardest game in SEO — unless you show up with something the recipient already wanted. That is why broken link building beats every other cold tactic on response rate. The offer is not "please link to me"; it is "your page is broken, and I fixed it for you."</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is broken link building?</h2>
        <p>Broken link building is an SEO strategy where you find dead outbound links (usually 404 errors) on other websites, create replacement content on your site, and ask the site owner to link to your content instead. Ahrefs research shows the average website has 5-15% broken outbound links — meaning almost every niche has abundant opportunity.</p>
        <p>The three ingredients:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>A broken link on a relevant, authoritative page</li>
          <li>Replacement content that matches or exceeds the original</li>
          <li>Polite, personalized outreach to the person who can update the link</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why it works</div>
          <p>Every dead outbound link hurts the site's user experience and — indirectly — its own SEO. Webmasters want to fix them. Your outreach is not a favor request; it is unsolicited help. That inversion is why broken link building consistently outperforms every other cold link-building tactic.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-works">Why broken link building works</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Mutual value.</strong> You get a <a href="/glossary/backlinks/">backlink</a>; the webmaster fixes a broken link and improves their site's UX and SEO.</li>
          <li><strong>Scalable.</strong> With Ahrefs or Semrush you can surface hundreds of relevant broken links per hour.</li>
          <li><strong>Topically aligned.</strong> Because you target pages already covering your topic, every earned link is highly relevant.</li>
          <li><strong>Relationship-building.</strong> Helpful outreach starts warmer conversations that pay off in guest posts, mentions, and future collaborations.</li>
          <li><strong>Google-safe.</strong> The tactic gives value to both sides and is treated as a natural editorial link, not a paid or exchange placement.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">The broken link building process — 4 steps</h2>

        <h3>Step 1 — Find broken links</h3>
        <p>Three methods, in order of scalability:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Competitor backlink analysis.</strong> Load a competitor's domain into Ahrefs or Semrush, filter their backlinks for 404 responses, and inspect the referring pages for topical fit.</li>
          <li><strong>Resource-page prospecting.</strong> Search operators like <code>&quot;keyword&quot; inurl:resources</code> or <code>&quot;keyword&quot; intitle:&quot;links&quot;</code> surface curated resource pages, then a Check My Links Chrome extension flags every broken outbound link on the page.</li>
          <li><strong>Large-scale crawling.</strong> Crawl target domains with Screaming Frog or Ahrefs Site Audit and export the broken outbound links table.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 2 — Vet the opportunity</h3>
        <p>Not every broken link is worth chasing. Evaluate on five criteria:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><a href="/glossary/domain-authority/">Domain authority</a> or DR — is the linking site actually influential?</li>
          <li>Niche relevance — does the page's topic overlap with yours?</li>
          <li>Link context — is the anchor and surrounding text something your content can plausibly replace?</li>
          <li>Number of broken links on the page — pages with many broken links suggest an inactive editor</li>
          <li>Page traffic — pages that still get search or referral traffic pass more equity</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 3 — Create the replacement content</h3>
        <p>Use the <a href="https://web.archive.org/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Wayback Machine</a> to view what the original content covered. Your replacement should:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Cover the same topic comprehensively</li>
          <li>Offer newer information, updated data, or a fresher angle</li>
          <li>Present better design or structure than the archived original</li>
          <li>Add value the original lacked (extra examples, downloadable checklist, embedded video)</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Step 4 — Outreach</h3>
        <p>Concise, personalized, under 150 words. Rules that raise response rate:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Get to the point in the first sentence — "I noticed one of your links is broken."</li>
          <li>Show you actually read the page — reference the specific broken link and its context</li>
          <li>Suggest, do not demand — "if you find it useful"</li>
          <li>Provide the replacement URL and a one-line reason it fits</li>
          <li>Follow up once after 5-7 days if there is no response — then stop</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="tools">Broken link building tools</h2>
        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Tool</th><th>Purpose</th><th>Cost</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight"><td><strong>Ahrefs</strong></td><td>Find broken backlinks + competitor analysis</td><td>Paid</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Semrush</strong></td><td>Broken link detection + backlink analysis</td><td>Paid</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Screaming Frog</strong></td><td>Crawl sites for broken outbound links</td><td>Free (500 URLs) / Paid</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Check My Links</strong></td><td>Chrome extension for on-page broken link detection</td><td>Free</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Wayback Machine</strong></td><td>View archived versions of dead pages</td><td>Free</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hunter.io</strong></td><td>Find email addresses for outreach</td><td>Freemium</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>BuzzStream</strong></td><td>Outreach tracking + follow-up management</td><td>Paid</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real broken link building examples</h2>

        <h3>1. The competitor-backlink flip</h3>
        <p>SaaS marketer exports the top 500 backlinks of the category leader from Ahrefs and filters for 404 responses. 34 broken links on relevant pages. They rebuild the original content (using Wayback) as an updated 2026 version, send 34 personalized emails, and win 6 replacement backlinks — response rate: 17.6%.</p>

        <h3>2. Resource-page hunt in the finance niche</h3>
        <p>Personal-finance blogger uses <code>&quot;personal finance&quot; inurl:resources</code> to find 120 resource pages. Check My Links flags 41 with at least one broken link. They send 41 outreach emails and win 4 links from DR 60+ sites — response rate: 10%.</p>

        <h3>3. The scale-and-vet counter-example</h3>
        <p>Agency sends 800 automated emails offering their new guide as a replacement. Zero personalization, zero mention of the specific broken link on the target page. Response rate: 0.4%. Lesson: personalization is the moat.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Broken link building vs guest posting — which to prioritize</h2>
        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Broken link building</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Response rate: 5-15%</li>
              <li>Time per link: ~1 hour incl. content</li>
              <li>Content: existing pages plus updates</li>
              <li>Relationship depth: light</li>
              <li>Best for: volume link acquisition</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4><a href="/glossary/guest-posting/">Guest posting</a></h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Response rate: 1-5% for cold pitches</li>
              <li>Time per link: 6-12 hours (pitch + article)</li>
              <li>Content: new article per placement</li>
              <li>Relationship depth: strong</li>
              <li>Best for: authority + traffic on top-tier sites</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p>Run both. Broken link building drives volume; guest posting drives depth. Most SEO teams allocate 60/40 between the two in early-stage link building.</p>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for broken link building</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritize relevance over authority.</strong> A DR 45 link from a topically aligned site beats a DR 75 link from an off-topic one.</li>
          <li><strong>Rebuild, do not repackage.</strong> Replacement content must be visibly superior to the archived original — new data, new structure, or a new angle.</li>
          <li><strong>Personalize every email.</strong> Reference the specific broken link URL and one detail from the target page. Mass templates get ignored.</li>
          <li><strong>Send from a real person, not <code>outreach@</code>.</strong> Response rates on named senders are 2-3x higher than generic aliases.</li>
          <li><strong>Follow up exactly once.</strong> 5-7 days after the initial. More follow-ups annoy editors and burn your domain.</li>
          <li><strong>Track by campaign, not by link.</strong> A 10% response rate over 100 emails is normal; judging individual emails as failures wastes energy.</li>
          <li><strong>Feed replacement content back into your <a href="/glossary/internal-linking/">internal linking</a>.</strong> Every replacement page should link to two or three of your other pages to distribute the new authority you earn.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — mass-sending generic emails</div>
          <p>The single fastest way to kill a broken link building campaign is to send the same template to 500 sites. Response rates crater to below 1% and your sending domain gets flagged as spam. Personalize every send, or send fewer.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common broken link building mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Mediocre replacement content.</strong> Editors will not link if your version is not visibly better than the archived original.</li>
          <li><strong>Targeting low-quality sites.</strong> Focus on authoritative, relevant domains. Spammy directory links hurt more than they help.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring existing content.</strong> Update and improve a current page before creating a new one.</li>
          <li><strong>Giving up after one campaign.</strong> A 10% response rate is normal; scale is what makes it work.</li>
          <li><strong>No follow-up.</strong> The single reminder email often earns more responses than the original.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is broken link building in simple terms?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>You find a dead link on someone else's website, offer them a live replacement from your own site, and ask them to update the link. It works because webmasters want to fix broken links — your outreach solves their problem.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What is a good response rate for broken link building?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>5-15% is the typical range. A 10% response rate is considered excellent. If you email 100 relevant sites and secure 10 backlinks, that is a successful campaign. Response rate depends heavily on relevance, replacement content quality, and personalization.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">What tools do I need for broken link building?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>At minimum: Ahrefs or Semrush for finding broken backlinks, Screaming Frog or Check My Links for on-page detection, Wayback Machine for viewing original content, and Hunter.io for finding email addresses. A tool like BuzzStream helps at scale for outreach tracking.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">How long does a broken link building campaign take?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>A single campaign of 100 outreach emails typically runs 3-4 weeks: 1 week to find opportunities, 1 week to create replacement content, 1 week to send outreach, and 1 week for follow-ups. Full results appear 4-8 weeks after outreach as sites update their pages and Google recrawls.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)"><span class="faq-q-text">Is broken link building white-hat SEO?</span><span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span></button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes. Broken link building is one of the safest link-building tactics because it provides genuine value to the receiving site — you help them fix a broken link. Google has never treated it as manipulative when done relevantly and without paying for placement.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

